<br>
On to Brotherscale's remarks, didn't get a chance to read 'em before posting.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As I said, I feel they must have been placed into custody for a reason.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Didn't I make myself clear?  The majority of detainees there were picked up in <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>random sweeps</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  That means the only reason they were arrested is that they lived in the same neighborhood as a suspect.  A reason I grant you, but a bad reason.  Civvies having their door broken down at 3am and picked up for no better reason than living in a suspicious neighborhood isn't the best way to turn Iraqis against the insurgency is it.<br>
<br>
You say in custody for a reason.  That reason isn't disclosed to anyone, not even to the detainee after months of detention.  It could be that he just &quot;looks shifty&quot; or it might be more substantial.  If Specialist Jeremy Sivits and the other 7-8 charged deserve due process, then why don't the innocents picked up in random sweeps?  Unless you're saying everyone in the neighborhoods swept deserved to be detained without due process, I think you've failed to respond to the point.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And as far as taking the US appointed CPA's statements at face value I don't know their credentials other than Paul Bremmer (and even then I am not intimately familiar).  The CPA is UN appointed as I remember as well but I may be wrong. And anything appointed by the UN is suspect in my eyes.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Ummm, you might want to do your research on who is in charge of Iraq at the moment.  The CPA was appointed by the United States government executive branch.  After June 30th they will form the backbone of the largest embassy of any country anywhere in the world- over 2,000 full-time American staff employed.  As for their credentials, most of them were selected by the Pentagon.  <br>
<br>
As for what you say about the UN, it astonishes me.  Every successful post-conflict resolution in the last two decades has involved the UN (of which the US is a powerful member might I add).  From Cyprus to Sierra Leone to Bosnia to Kosovo and in Eritrea the UN has brought peace to parts of the world that had seen ethnic strife and civil war for hundreds of years.  If the UN had been on board from the beginning of the conflict as a truly international effort, I doubt the Iraqi Governing Council (IGC) would be seen as illegitimate and unpopular as they clearly are now.  Prime Minister Allawi was likely appointed by the CPA because he has long-standing ties to British and US intelligence that pre-date the Saddam regime.  <br>
<br>
So when the CPA admits that most of them are civilians being combed through like plankton through a whale's mouth, you know they're being accurate.  After all, as part of a US executive government branch, it is in the CPA's best interest to maximize the number of terrorists and &quot;evildoers&quot; and minimize the number of innocents held- for PR reasons on the ground.  It wouldn't suprise me if the 70-80% figure is lower than the actual amount.  Don't forget that in the absence of Spc Darby and other anonymous sources, we might never have known about these abuses.  This administration is the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://writ.news.findlaw.com/dean/20020524.html" target="top">most secretive since Nixon</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> according to Nixon's legal counsel John Dean, and he should know.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now, as to the people who you quoted as being allied with our cause. I can't say why they would have made those statements but until I know otherwise they might be under duress due to certain conditions we are not aware of (such as threats or family issues) or their views might have changed. We just don't know since we weren't there<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Are you saying because we weren't there we should ignore the corroboration of people that were there?  General Taguba corroborated it in his report.  He wasn't there either, but statements from people witnessing it were in his report.  I guess he's lying huh...he wasn't there!  Suppose the defence attorneys are lying about the corroboration they have too.  <br>
<br>
It seems for you, not knowing the facts is a translation for &quot;Support the administration!&quot;  Bit of a slanted view that<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And I did not make the argument in favor of torture for strategic benefit. I stated that in the case to preserve noncombatants when I KNEW the person was in possesion of certain information. Scroll back up and re-read it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well how do you KNOW if someone is in possession of certain information?  Plus, if you suspect that someone is plotting an unconventional attack, and you use brutal unconventional methods to stop them, how are you any better than the terrorist?  An insurgent might claim that he KNOWS the US will pull out of Fallujiah if a simple and brutal act forces a confrontation that the insurgency will be ready for.  That is both brutal and unconventional thinking- worse than what the US did, but using the same rationale you did.  That insurgent *knows* about US intentions of pulling out just as much as anyone can *know* whether someone is witholding information.  The abused man who is classified as a civilian detainee at the top of the statement, a designated non-combatant, are we now in the business of abusing civvies to get at information we think they have?  Stalin's secret police did much the same, many &quot;confessed&quot; fake crimes just to stop the beatings.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And again neither you nor I can know what information may have been gained. How do you know that information learned did not just save thousands of lives yet you will never hear about it due to operational security<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Because if *thousands* of lives had been saved it would be a HUGE propaganda coup for the coalition and they'd milk every last drop.  I can't believe the naive drivel that people say sometimes- if Osama bin Laden was captured, we'd all know, if an attack/attacks causing thousands of casualties were foiled we'd all know, because knowing that would increase support for the war amongst Iraqis, Americans and elsewhere.<br>
<br>
Plus, anyone with the vaguest knowledge of interrogation techniques knows that if you beat information out of someone, they'll likely resist, make something up, or tell you what you want to hear rather than what is really happening.  It <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>does not work</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Similar strong-arm techniques were used on hundreds of Vietcong detainees to gain information on the Tet offensive, history shows how useful that was :P  Not to mention if someone finds their conscience like Spc Darby and it comes out, you can kiss hearts and minds goodbye.  <br>
<br>
Cracking down so to speak will not eliminate the insurgency, it will likely increase overall public support for it.  Particularly if the majority of those detained/abused were civilians.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Also as to Iraq not being a threat it was not only to hunt WMDs that we invaded.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Really?  Hate to be pedantic, but the justification for war in UNSCR 1441 was that if Iraq didn't &quot;immediately disarm&quot; its WMDs &quot;serious consequences&quot; would follow.  There was no mention in the resolution of proliferation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Sadaam Husein was known to fund groups that were hostile to the West, specifically the USA. Now, lets say he were to fund one of these groups with enough <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's just the point isn't it- can you start a war with nothing more than fear, paranoia and assertions?  There's no proof of what you say because if there was it would have been presented, if not to us then to allies in closed session.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The people who made the decision to invade went forward with the information they had. And call me naive but I tend to believe they have more complete information in most ways then is available to the general public<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Then why not simply disclose it?  Just do it to the Senate intelligence committee behind closed doors like the 9/11 intelligence which contained sensitive sources.  There is no proof of it, not a shred, simply their assertions and fears of what might happen.  It's terribly hit and miss- it's war justified via Pin the Tail on the Donkey compounded with fear.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My foe in this case kills noncombatants, women, children, specifically for the purpose of inflicting terror and fear<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Specifically for the purpose of ending the occupation.  That they use terror and fear for their goals is no different from you using terror and fear to achieve yours.  You claim destroying peoples' lives will save other lives, I'm sure they claim the same after seeing their families maimed and dead in the hospitals and described as &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.iraqbodycount.net/" target="top">collateral damage</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;.  Both lines of thinking are barbaric.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I really am not going to have my feelings hurt, since I do not harm without good reason. But give me a good reason and all bets are off.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I'm sure that many insurgents will undoubtedly say exactly the same thing.  Al-Qaeda already have said exactly what you said.  It all amounts to what you or they consider &quot;good reason&quot;.  For you brutal actions are justified if you think they will end up saving lives and ending enemy life.  That is the insurgency's justification too- that brutal actions will save the lives of their bretheren and help win the conflict.  <br>
<br>
And I think both views are dead wrong.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Is it Osama and gang? well they booted to Afghanistan, and the fighting in Afghanistan gets about as much play on the U.S. news Channels as the Calgary Flames<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The Afghanistan policy has been all but abandoned- Hamid Karzai is still jokingly called the Mayor of Kabul, since his writ extends no further.  There simply aren't the boots on the ground to take the country back from the warlords running most of it.  The story died because it wasn't changing.  &quot;Karzai Still Powerless&quot;  and &quot;Warlords Still Running the South&quot; peter out as headlines.  Whereas in Iraq the issue has been forced by a war of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>choice</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and Bush has bet his presidency on its success.  Also, the casualty rate has been higher in Iraq, although they are still happening in Afghanistan.  Pat Tilman got coverage because of the stupendous sacrifice he made- but that's about it.<br>
<br>
Oh and if the Flames don't win today they'll have only themselves to blame.  They've dominated the series, TB deserved to win only one of those games and ended up pinching a second.  I lost count of the number of times TB iced the puck in the last game, that's how much Calgary dominated.  Seem a bit brittle on confidence though, took them OT to win a game they dominated.  Be nice to see a Canuck team win for a change though eh? <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
