 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tomstrife>tomstrife</A> at: 6/5/04 4:19 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=taranna>Taranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>HiElf Snob</span><br>  Posts: 1095<br> <font color=#333333>(6/5/04 6:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2705.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: geez</span><hr size=1> They aren't essays Fepp, I spend between 5 and 7 minutes writing them.  You spend more time afk at raids than I do writing these posts :P  I'll let the audience decide whether being afk in a game, or discussing things I find interesting is a bigger waste of time!<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Watching TV, after seeing commercials and women with large chests, they would be striving to nail a hot girl - and it makes you want to give up religion/politics/etc for secular goods.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Er, that's total crap, bullshit and poppycock- ask any sociologist.  Continental Europe in several countries show pornography, pretty graphic pornography on terrestrial TV channels, network TV and free to air stations.  They still care deeply about the outside world.  You can't live in a glass bubble, for reasons of international trade, relations and because terrorism has no borders.  The isolationist view is so ridiculous and retrodden I feel it does not merit a response. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As your statement about prisoners in the US, a lot of people are jailed up without bail until their trials<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Whether or not to grant bail is decided in a court-room hearing and by due process of law- you can't get away from that.  Iraqi civilians have no recourse of law to challenge their detention in any way.  That is what makes the responsibility of occupying another country fraught with policy conundrums.<br>
<br>
How is it possible to say for example, that establishing democracy is a goal if the concept of innocence before proven guilt is absent in the behavior of occupying forces?  In the occupations of Germany and Japan, the burden was shared successfully and civilians had the right to challenge their detention.  It was that successful post-war transition that allowed Germany and Japan to grow into the nations we see today.  That was a war of necessity without certainty of victory- this was a war of choice where victory was never in doubt.  Why then Tomza, has the post-war plan failed in so many key areas, and why are Iraqis innocents still bereft of fundamental rights that we promised them?<br>
<br>
No one's saying that the US troops are doing anything wrong- just that the policies are wrong, dead wrong.  But it's not the policymakers facing the bullets and bombs is it?  Only one congressman has a son in military service, neither President nor Vice-President have even smelled a war.  Yet it is their policies that have killed many of the 800+ service personnel and 10,000 Iraqi civilians.  Still, not one person losing their job over the various fiascos, where is the accountability Tomza?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for prisoners in Iraq, even if they were innocent civilians, how many of them were are the wrong place where they shouldnt be at the wrong time<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
We're there to bring democracy and you have no problem with people being arrested for being in the wrong place at the wrong time?  <br>
<br>
Also, most of the civilians were held for months, some since the prison was rebuilt.  No curfew works that way, save in brutal police states- Saddam did that sort of thing- if we follow suit even half-way to that, then our moral justification for invading begins to crumble decisively.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>after curfew or whatever to be picked up?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
See, this is why I wished people would do their research.  Most of the civilians were arrested in their own homes, there were entire residential areas where every young male of fighting age was detained.  This policy of sweeping neighborhoods and collectively punishing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>potential</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rebel sympathizers has a long history- from Nazi Germany's occupation of southern europe to Turkey's occupation of Armenia, to Russia's occupation of Afghanistan.  Not the best examples to be following.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Being in a &quot;war zone&quot; you think they would be smart enough to stay out of trouble<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If they were arrested in their own homes how are they causing trouble?  Many were too scared to go out after dark, the occupying power had failed to restore security.  Then your door gets broken down at 3am, and you get hauled off to a prison, bereft of even the most BASIC of rights.  And then held for 6 months, abused, tortured.  Put yourself in those peoples' shoes, and then it's not hard to reason out why the occupation is incredibly unpopular there and there's no shortage of ordinary people willing to fight the occupation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>they told me horrible stories of the VC using any kind of dirty tactic from using women, children and other methods to kill enemies<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not unlike the dirty tactics US citizens used to rightly throw out their occupiers.  Citizens fighting a vastly superior enemy and love their country will do almost anything to fight enemies invading their soil.  Plus Tomza you can't seriously ignore what the US did in Vietnam.  Carpet bombing, napalm, Agent Orange, destroying crops for entire regions, two million civilians killed, more bombs dropped than in WWI and WWII COMBINED...it wasn't a one-sided story by any means at all.  <br>
<br>
In one key respect, Vietnam was actually a *better* thought out intervention.  The South Vietnamese wanted the United States there, the US had allies on the ground willing to fight the enemy and help the US.  The same was true in Afghanistan (even if some of the were rather evil warlords).  In Iraq there is no local political group the US has worked with outside of the Kurds, and that is purely regional and expeditious.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You think there could be a possibility that one of these &quot;innocent civilians&quot; could be scouting - for when to have the next suicide bombing<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
See, I don't think that a &quot;possibility&quot; is enough to detain a majority of innocents and torture them.  Hell, I don't think torturing any enemy achieves anything except the radicalization of your enemy.  Iraq is largely a fiercely secular country with a secular political movement.  Torturing people, innocent or otherwise and aggressively making large decisions on their behalf (privatizing their ministries, awarding Iraqi government contracts to US companies)- if the US is trying to sow the seeds for another radical chaotic theocratic state, it's going about it the right way.  Just read about Mossadeq and Iran Tomza- and think about the consequences.<br>
<br>
Plus you haven't done your research again- pretty much all of the US soldiers who have died haven't died to suicide bombs.  Al-Qaeda have targeted US-appointed Iraqis who they've called puppets- they have been targeted by suicide bombers.<br>
<br>
Most of the US soldiers have been killed by conventional guerilla warfare using conventional weapons.  IEDs, rifles and grenades, much the same technique that any country would use in the event of invasion, including the United States.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Liberals think too idealistically<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I am neither a liberal nor an idealist, those are pigeon-holes.  There is good policy and bad policy- when I see good policy from anyone I praise it, when I see bad policy from anyone I condemn it.  You can't build achievement out of ideals alone, the cornerstone has to be good policy.  The invasion was a bad policy, the post-occupation plans have been bad policy and the means of power transfer is a bad policy.  The policy failures were predictable, hell I predicted many of them and I'm a private citizen reading about this on my own.  This is beyond ideology or simple political definitions, it is simply incompetent, from any side of the political spectrum.<br>
<br>
