I do when the joke is funny! :P<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Its closing to election time as well, for someone to lose their job and to take time to rehire someone else would waste more time<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Rubbish.  George Tenet resigned at short notice and his deputy will take over.  The DDO is resigning also, and business goes on as usual.  Standing policies are continued, there hasn't been major upheaval.  <br>
<br>
The fact that no one has even been reprimanded publicly, never mind fired sends the message that nothing has gone wrong.  That reinforces the statements of Al-Qaeda recruiters and will make life difficult for American troops and civilians long after this election.  Good government makes the right decision for the country on issues that important, irrespective of its re-election.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Even though of the detainee's in the high security wing of the prison where the abuse was taking place were being held on scant evidence, its being done partially for our security<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's what China says about Tibet, Russia says about Chechnya and indeed what Stalin said about Caucasus dissidents held in the Gulag.  Heck, it was Saddam's justification also.  How is the way these regimes have acted/are acting reprehensible torture, and what the US is doing necessary security measures?  Supporting the reasoning of one condones the actions of all of these regimes, for their justifications are the same.<br>
<br>
I suggest you go back to an earlier post I make on this thread, and with the help of Adobe Acrobat, read the sworn statements of the abused detainees.  Read about *exactly* what happened to them, and imagine how you'd feel if you were an innocent civilian (as in the first statement) and those same things happened to you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That is just like bail, lots of people who are deemed as violent and dangerous to the community are not granted bail, thus are imprisioned in there without a chance to leave. These people imprisioned are believed to hold information that could be important...<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Those refused bail had their chance to argue a right for bail in a court of law, I said that in my last post.  Can Iraqi civilians assess or challenge the reasons for their detention?  What trial do they await?  Have they been charged?  No, no and no.  It is disingenuous and specious to compare prisoners remanded without bail to Iraqi civilians detained with little or no evidence.  <br>
<br>
Due process is a fundamental prerequisite for a sustainable democracy.  In its absence what you have is a military police state.  If you're ok with a military police state Tomza, then say so clearly.  If you're not ok with such a state, then the detentions are undemocratic, unjustified and should be stopped.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yea its sad that some died, but after some time a lot of them were released<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
They were only released after the photos and sworn statements were published in tandem with the Taguba report.  It shouldn't take a scandal for the occupying power to do the right thing.  The release had nothing to do with a routine discharge, a HUGE number of people were all released a week after the scandal broke.  Remember also, the seven soldiers charged were only charged AFTER the photos were released, despite the fact that these photos were in military files and referenced in the Taguba report.<br>
<br>
There would have been no serious action taken without the photos going public.  That alone should make you question the policy.  Rather than saying they were released- look at *why* they were released *when* they were released and how many were released.  Looking at it in context, it's no longer as simple as you make it out.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but there is a possibility that it could potentially harvest very important information<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>These people imprisioned are believed to hold information that could be important<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&quot;The possibility of potentially harvesting&quot;....&quot;are believed to hold information&quot;, is that justification in your mind for holding thousands of prisoners incommunicado for 6 months to a year and torturing them?  I've got a better idea- why doesn't the occupying authority just manage the occupation more humanely.  That way we won't have to fucking <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>torture</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it out of people, they'll come forward and willingly tell us.  <br>
<br>
Willing informants is how Qusay and Uday were tracked down, it was how Saddam Hussein was tracked down.  Indeed, the CPA has confirmed that with the exception of those who surrendered themselves, almost every other senior Ba'ath minister was captured as the result of a willing informant.<br>
<br>
The vast majority of the security information you have referred to has been accrued via willing informants and voluntary cooperation.  We shouldn't have to torture people when our best information has come from cooperative sources.  People are being told to come forward, but the fear of torture will drive many to the other side, or silence people that would otherwise cooperate.  As I said, torture means you kiss hearts and minds goodbye, do you concede that?  Or do you think hearts and minds are unimportant as long as a small-scale security goal is accomplished, by any means necessary?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but I know if America pulled out early <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I never said the US should pull out.  Although I opposed the policy of invasion, I feel it would be irresponsible to leave right now.  You said &quot;if America pulled out early&quot;.  Earlier than what?  How long should American troops stay?  &quot;Until the job is done&quot; is a much-used cliche, but when is the job done.  When a democracy is established?  It will take more than a year to train even a skeleton security force.  After security- what about the institutions of government?  They're a major part of democracy after all, and many, such as a department of labor, take years and many billions to establish.  <br>
<br>
What I am getting at is the abysmal lack of an exit strategy, beyond saying &quot;until the job is done&quot;, when no one has the faintest idea what that means.  Any more than when that big &quot;Mission Accomplished&quot; banner hung across an aircraft carrier deck with the President standing in front of it.  Beyond a cheap stunt and political chicanery, that banner and saying &quot;until the job is done&quot; are policy equivalents.  I see no obvious or definite exit strategy nor a justification for its choice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Just look at history and the numerous times it has been done, and I dont think its ever changing. (I dont think its right, but it happens, wont change)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
So you're essentially saying we should all accept injustice today because there has always been injustice.  If people took that attitude then segregation and apartheid would still be around, Nazi germany would be a superpower and commercial slavery would be widespread.  <br>
<br>
That's why I find the tone of what you say there utterly repulsive to me.  Because at the time slavery was abolished in British and the Commonwealth, people with the same views as you stood up and said &quot;But there's always been slavery in history, what can we do about it?&quot;  All that is needed is for enough people to know a policy is unjust, to express it, and then to do it.  <br>
<br>
That is what democracy is, the idea of democracy cannot begin and end with the casting of a vote at the ballot box.  If it is not a continuous process of engagement with the issues, then we *will* see injustice continue.  But history also teaches us Tomza, that with enough of the right people doing the right thing, injustice is defeated.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I think there should be a greater watch on the other countries that could potentially build nuclear weapons and sell them to terrorist groups<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's where I agree with you 150%.  Imagine if the massive human and budget resources poured and still being emptied into Iraq had instead been focused on Afghanistan and counterterrorism.  Just take the 87 billion dollar post-war supplemental, think what 87 billion dollars in counter-terrorism efforts would have done for American and global security.  <br>
<br>
That same security was not served by the Iraq war, but it would be served by spending the money and resources to defeat terrorism and *real* threats, not perceived threats.  Because of failed intelligence and a fanatical faith-based approach to Iraq, billions of dollars and thousands of lives have been wasted.  Perhaps if those billions of dollars and the resources they accrued had been spent on *intelligence* in the first place, the mistake would not have been made.  By intelligence I don't mean torture, but ELINT/surveillance, and HUMINT/tradecraft.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but what happened in this prison I believe was done in the best interest of a larger majority<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's exactly what the Nazis told each other about their &quot;Final solution&quot; too, it's exactly how the brutal excesses of South African apartheid were rationalized too.  Justifying brutality and oppression by declaring it in the majority interest means nothing without understanding what really happens.  Torture creates more terrorists, it alienates the local populace, endangers the lives of Americans, whether soldier or civilian and it's just plain WRONG.  None of the impacts of torture on the balance-sheet, serve a larger majority.  On balance in fact, everyone loses.  You can't justify it morally or strategically, it's a disaster in both senses.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But I also like to think practically, there are some things that have to be done that break the rules<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That's another thing terrorists frequently say to justify what they do.  In fact, when devout muslims often tell terrorists what they are doing is against God's rules, they simply reply with what you said.  &quot;Practically you have to break the rules sometimes or there won't be anyone to follow God's rules&quot;.  Both arguments reek of bullshit to me.  <br>
<br>
Murder is murder, torture is torture and brutality is brutality.  You stop believing that and we might as well not be fighting terrorism.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Btw, if you were wondering, I have no strong political stance<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Without going out on a limb, I'd say that condoning the trial-free detention and torture of innocent civilians is a pretty strong political stance.  I'd also say that it is the stance of an extremist and not a moderate.  Simply because moderates seek negotiated compromise and extremists argue that there is only one violent solution.  That's what you're saying- we can't talk to local leaders or promote humane understanding, the only way you seem to believe works is to detain and torture these people.  I'd call that as extremist a view as those fundamentalists who say American power can't be reasoned with, the only way to deal with it is through &quot;glorious martyrdom&quot;.  Bullshit, and bullshit on both counts.  On a quick side note for the less informed- the word &quot;jihad&quot; does not mean holy war, it means &quot;struggle&quot; and the context of its use in Arab vernacular means a &quot;righteous struggle&quot;.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yea, if we werent in Iraq in the first place doing it the way we are doing, this would not even need to happen, but since we are, I feel that certain things that were being done are justified<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Again, let's draw a parallel.  Many extremist but non-militant Muslims (similar to Christian groups that support the Iraq war but refuse to serve on religious grounds)- have said the same thing about 9/11 and the attacks that follow it.  Namely that they wish 9/11 hadn't happened the way it happened, but now that the jihad has begun, they can see the way clear to justify what is being done.  <br>
<br>
You and the extremists who support 9/11 after it happened, have essentially flip-flopped on core values of morality.  You say in peacetime that you would never support such brutality, but you believe current circumstances dictate that brutality is necessary.  Many Islamic extremists say that in peacetime, the killing of innocents is utterly forbidden, but given the threat the US poses to the Islamic way of life after decades of injustice and the Iraq war, and there is a jihad, that they too have to say brutality is necessary.  Both views are repugnant to me, both emphasize fear and icy pragmatism that lead to &quot;justifiable brutality&quot; and the kind of injustice that history will judge unkindly to say the least.<br>
<br>
If our values as a society regarding trial-free detention and torture support such barbarity to greater and greater extents, then there will come a point where the defeat of terrorism won't even matter, since our moral and social fabrics are that much less distinguishable from those of terrorists.  Those who have read Orwell's book <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Animal Farm</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(1946) and understand its significance, I will now remind you of the last two sentences-<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Twelve voices were shouting in anger, and they were all alike. No question, now, what had happened to the faces of the pigs. The creatures outside looked from pig to man, and from man to pig, and from pig to man again; but already it was impossible to say which was which.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
That is what worries me most of all, that enough people with Tomza's views will tolerate torture and abuse as long as they *think* it is serving a useful end.  Either that or simply wallow in apathy saying that &quot;history proves bad things always happen so why bother about anything&quot;.  In that pragmatic and taciturn approval of brutality and barbarism, we see a far more insidious threat to democratic values- the willingness to ignore hellish wrongdoing to serve the goals of a failed policy.  Those have been the hallmarks of brutal dictators since the dawn of time- even the slightest similarity of justification should sicken us,  but the shocking extent of how similar the views are, is what I have attempted to illustrate here.<br>
<br>
Just one last point Tomza- I'm curious to know how you think torturing a majority of innocents serves the innocent majority?  If it is because they might have provided crucial information, they haven't- our best info has come from willing sources.  I can't see another reason you'd think it justifiable.  And perhaps, given that you think it's ok for &quot;imminent&quot; threats, you would consider crime in the US an imminent threat to citizen safety.  Then we could torture any innocent civilian in the US who we felt had information about a murder, rape or the drug trade.  Well if it's good for Iraqi innocents then why not American innocents?  Spread the love!<br>
<br>
<br>
PS-Abandon a confrontation, declare yourself the victor and then declare an isolationist stance and rant about nuking people.  Hey, if it worked with as an exit strategy for Vietnam then why shouldn't it work as one for Brotherscale too? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
PPS- I apologize for the subtley of the satire in the above postscript.<br>
<br>
