<br>
I will just make a few quick points.<br>
<br>
1.  when extremists murdered innnocent americans on the 11th september, did that make americans more or less determined to seek revenge on those extremists?<br>
2.  when americans tortured and murdered innocent iraqis, do you think that will make iraqis more or less determined to seek revenge on those americans?<br>
<br>
For the slow learners out there and those who don't like to follow the links, or read the reports, here are some things that are torture: raping young boys, beating the crap out of people until they pass out, sodomizing prisoners with batons and electric lights, forcing men to perform oral sex on other men, killing prisoners, striking broken legs until the prisoner condemns his god.<br>
I can't believe people are still fixated on these notions that this is just a bit of rambunctious good humour.  <br>
<br>
It seems that, unbelievably, it is necessary to mount an argument that torture is wrong.  It is unbelievable because america for so long as fostered noble ideas on freedom, liberty, bravery.  Why is a country so wedded to this high standing values using such base torture and why are its citizens defending it?<br>
The two defences coming forward seem to be: <br>
1. sometimes you have to play rough to get vital information to save lives.<br>
2.  these guys we are arresting are 'interogatting' are terrorists anyway.<br>
<br>
The first defence is the classic utilitarian/absolutist moral paradigm about the use of torture.  A terrorist has a nuclear bomb which will detonate unless he tells you how to disarm it. Is it legitimate to torture that information out of him to save the lives of so many people?  In this archetypal situation, people generally plump for utilitarianism - that it is better to save the most lives and we should torture.<br>
However, we aren't talkign here about a primed nuclear device.  We are talking about standard intelligence collection.  From what does the imperative to torture spring?  Do we torture muggers or thieves? What about those who drive drunk or speed their cars?<br>
<br>
The second defence makes for some nice circular reasoning.  We only arrest terrorists. You are arrested. Therefore you must be a terrorist.  The Red Cross put out a report recently that 80% of the people arrested where ordinary civilians.  How much irreperable damage does it do to your aims if you torture &quot;innocent civilians&quot;.  Justifying their torture and killing is as obscene as trying to justify killing americans in the twin towers attack.<br>
<br>
Let me tell you waht happens if you torture and kill innocent civilians.  they hate you.  they hate your country.  they join paramilitary organisations who bomb and kill your civilians.  Every time Israel demolishes a palestinian house, they create new martyrs.  Look at britain, stauch ally in &quot;the war on terror&quot;, everytime they perpetuated some atrocity on the irish, a new generation of fighters was born, sworn to kill &quot;the brits&quot;.<br>
