Are you high?  9/10 of those statements are corroborated by photos, video footage and the General A. Taguba report, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a report by the offending agent of abuse</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> which corroborates the statements.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But why tell the truth when you can make the people imprisoning you look worse<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Yeah, and I'm sure every woman that was ever raped exaggerated her story, I'm also sure that without the video evidence you'd have said that Rodney King was talking bullshit and exaggerating what happened to him.  Here's what I find amusing about your statement- General A. Taguba, a US army general investigating the abuse was a lot harsher in his descriptions of the happenings than the sworn statements of the abused were.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I said that I think it was sad that they were being tortured<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I'm sure that's of great comfort to prison suspects in all police states everywhere- that a free citizen condones torture but finds it &quot;sad&quot;.  I'm sure that Al-Qaeda and China/Russia are praying every day that more people think like Tomza- it'll continue to make the US look worse than its once high standards, and make Al-Qaeda and these regimes look less bad.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but even then, the torture they endure arent things like having your arms stretched by ropes or anything<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You admit in the thread that you didn't read any of the statements (which as I say have been corroborated)- then you say the torture they underwent wasn't that bad.<br>
<br>
In the first of the statements (corroborated by US military witnesses in the Taguba report, photographs and medical reports)- a detainee had his leg broken by guards.  Then a guard kicked it repeatedly until it fractured contiguously shouting at the inmate to renounce his religion.  In another case a prisoner was sodomized by a guard, in yet another section of the Taguba report (not prisoner statements) it says prisoners were raped.<br>
<br>
Most men or women would rather endure physical punishment to a great degree rather than rape.  I don't think you can speak so dismissively of innocent people being thrashed and raped by a foreign army.  If it was happening to innocent Americans occupied by a foreign power...I think you'd change your tune Tomza, and in a heartbeat.  I don't think that as an American you'd accept the rape, murder, beatings, crawling over broken glass and humiliation of innocent fellow citizens in the name of your security.  <br>
<br>
Now if you wouldn't accept it happening to innocent Americans on a large scale, why would you tolerate it for Iraqis?  And why would you assume they accepted it for their security- they certainly weren't asked.  Why for that matter would you assume that innocent Iraqi civilians would lie about their captors?  The Taguba report doesn't support that, and being an army report it has every incentive to discredit the detainee statements.  Instead it backs them pretty much to the hilt.  <br>
<br>
You're running out of justification for this torture.  <br>
<br>
&quot;They're lying&quot;-  WRONG<br>
<br>
&quot;It's necessary for our security&quot;- If you believe that then you must also openly condone what China does in Tibet, Russia does in Chechnya and what North Koreans do to South Korean military personnel.  <br>
<br>
&quot;If needed, certain liberties can be taken away&quot;-  When those liberties include basic human rights, innocent until proven guilty, and the removal of right to challenge detention, then there is little left that resembles a democracy.  Saying we have to act like a Saddamist dictatorship to establish democracy is also bullshit- acting like Saddam in even the slightest way will doom the policy and the occupation.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm a moderate, therefore it is ok for me to think this way&quot;-  I find it interesting that Hitler, Stalin, Pol Pot and Mao Tse-Tung all considered themselves moderates when asked about terrible human rights abuses.  A political pigeon-hole doesn't justify barbaric behavior.  Any more than a fundamentalist shit proudly calling himself Al-Qaeda excuses the murderous butchery that he condones.  <br>
<br>
I've explained to you that torture accrues no benefit, that there is no plausible justification without accepting the policies of a police state.<br>
<br>
Either you think torture is wrong, or you think a police state is acceptable in Iraq, even though democracy is the goal.  If the latter is your belief then state it clearly- say &quot;Stalin had the right idea, I just want to limit those brutal ideas a little for our security's sake.&quot;<br>
<br>
It'd make the exchange of ideas a lot easier incidentally, if you examined the evidence and defined your stance on brutal torture a bit better.<br>
<br>
<br>
EDIT:  Read Bollix's post and agree with it totally- he has a way of crystallizing the moral questions raised that I envy.  What he says is regarding Northern Ireland is all true- Bloody Sunday had a far smaller world-wide impact than Abu Ghraib, but its eventual consequences were catastrophic for the security situation.  The same was true of the Guildford Four and the abuses at Belmarsh where *suspected* IRA civilian informants had their faces burned off with blow-torches until they &quot;confessed&quot;.  On that occasion the US stood up and said the right thing- these days, Tomza's views seem more prevalent than ever before, both in government and on the street.  What a terrible shame.  Saddam must be clapping his hands and saying &quot;That's the way lads!&quot;<br>
